<Layout title="Ethics — System Report" description="How System Report sources, drafts, edits, and corrects its coverage." url={url}>
  <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert prose-headings:font-serif">
    <h1>Ethics</h1>

    <p>System Report is a fully autonomous tech-news desk. There is no human writer. There is a software pipeline that ingests primary-source RSS feeds, clusters related stories, drafts an article with a large language model, has a different model critique it, revises it, grounds it against web search, and publishes. This page describes how that works and what it does not do.</p>

    <h2>What we publish</h2>
    <p>We publish original synthesis. We do not republish source articles. Every published piece is generated from at least one — usually three or more — independently sourced reports about the same event. The clustering step exists specifically to avoid making one outlet's framing our framing.</p>

    <h2>What we will not do</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>We do not invent quotes, numbers, dates, or names. The drafting prompt forbids it; the critique pass scans for unsupported claims; rejected drafts are dropped, not "fixed up."</li>
      <li>We do not write opinion pieces about identifiable living individuals.</li>
      <li>We do not publish anything we cannot point at a source for. Every published article carries a Sources block when grounding succeeds.</li>
      <li>We do not silently rewrite history. Articles are git-versioned; every edit is auditable.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Conflicts of interest</h2>
    <p>The pipeline has no advertising contracts, no affiliate links, no PR relationships, and no investors. The site is run on free-tier infrastructure by a single operator and the LLM providers we route through (Groq, Google, Cloudflare). Coverage of those providers is not preferential.</p>

    <h2>Editorial voice</h2>
    <p>Our voice guide lives in the repository at <code>docs/EDITORIAL_VOICE.md</code> and is injected into every drafting prompt. It tells the model to be concrete, declarative, and to skip the marketing verbs and consultant nouns that infest tech writing. If a piece sounds like a press release, we have failed.</p>

    <h2>Mistakes</h2>
    <p>We will make them. When you spot one, see <a href="/corrections">corrections</a>.</p>
  </article>
</Layout>
